---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import PageHero from '../../components/PageHero.astro';
import LedgerCard from '../../components/LedgerCard.astro';
import TrusteeDuties from '../../components/TrusteeDuties.astro';
import CrossBridge from '../../components/CrossBridge.astro';
---
<BaseLayout
  title="Legal Desk · OASTL"
  description="Where the Oregon school-trust case is documented, tracked, and pursued. Court of Appeals ruling, lead counsel, current campaign, and the trustee-duties framework that grounds the litigation."
  path="/legal-desk/"
>
  <PageHero
    eyebrow="Legal Desk"
    title="Where the Oregon case is documented, tracked, and pursued."
    dek="The legal record is the spine of OASTL’s work. This is the page beneficiaries, journalists, and future plaintiffs come back to."
  />

  <!-- Section 1 — January 28, 2026 ruling -->
  <section class="bg-oastl-bone">
    <div class="mx-auto max-w-4xl px-5 py-16">
      <div class="font-mono text-[11px] tracking-[0.22em] uppercase text-oastl-gold mb-2">
        Section 1 · The ruling
      </div>
      <h2 class="font-serif text-3xl md:text-4xl text-oastl-forest font-semibold leading-tight">
        January 28, 2026 — <em>Advocates for School Trust Lands v. State of Oregon</em>
      </h2>
      <div class="mt-6 space-y-4 text-[17px] text-oastl-ink/85 leading-relaxed font-serif">
        <p>
          On January 28, 2026, the Oregon Court of Appeals issued a precedential ruling in
          <em>Advocates for School Trust Lands v. State of Oregon</em>. The Court reversed the trial court’s dismissal of OASTL’s suit and held that Oregon schoolchildren — the beneficiaries of the Common School Fund — have legal standing to hold the State accountable for the management of the trust.
        </p>
        <p>
          The reversal is a watershed for trust-lands litigation nationwide. For more than a century, the consistent procedural defense across the twenty trust-lands states has been that beneficiaries cannot sue. After January 28, 2026, that defense is no longer available in Oregon.
        </p>
        <p>
          The case now proceeds on the merits. OASTL is recruiting K-12 student co-plaintiffs whose names will appear in the next filings.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="mt-6 inline-block border border-oastl-blueprint/40 bg-oastl-cream/40 rounded-sm px-4 py-3 text-sm text-oastl-ink/80">
        {/* TODO[Dave]: insert link to the published opinion PDF once URL is captured */}
        <span class="font-mono text-[10px] tracking-[0.22em] uppercase text-oastl-blueprint">Pending</span>
        <span class="ml-2">Court opinion PDF — link to follow when Dave provides the URL.</span>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section 2 — Lead Appellate Counsel -->
  <section class="bg-oastl-cream/40 border-y border-oastl-forest/15">
    <div class="mx-auto max-w-4xl px-5 py-16">
      <div class="font-mono text-[11px] tracking-[0.22em] uppercase text-oastl-forest mb-2">
        Section 2 · Lead Appellate Counsel
      </div>
      <h2 class="font-serif text-3xl md:text-4xl text-oastl-ink font-semibold leading-tight">
        Natalie Scott — The Scott Law Group
      </h2>

      <LedgerCard tone="bone" class="mt-6">
        <div class="space-y-4 text-[16px] leading-relaxed">
          <p>
            <strong>Natalie Scott</strong>, founder of <strong>The Scott Law Group</strong>, served as Lead Appellate Counsel in the case OASTL won on January 28, 2026. Her brief and oral argument carried the standing question across the line.
          </p>
          <p>
            <strong>The Corvallis Effect.</strong> Oral arguments in the case were held at Corvallis High School with a student audience present. The strategic choice put the beneficiaries — Oregon schoolchildren — visibly in the room while the standing question was argued. Lawyers, journalists, and judges have remarked on the effect.
          </p>
          <p>
            <strong>The argument.</strong> Oregon’s constitutional duties to its schools are legally enforceable by the students themselves. Where the State has redirected the trust corpus or its income away from the common schools, the beneficiaries — not just a hypothetical attorney general — can sue.
          </p>
        </div>
      </LedgerCard>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section 3 — Current campaign -->
  <section class="bg-oastl-forest text-oastl-cream">
    <div class="mx-auto max-w-4xl px-5 py-16">
      <div class="font-mono text-[11px] tracking-[0.22em] uppercase text-oastl-gold mb-2">
        Section 3 · Current campaign
      </div>
      <h2 class="font-serif text-3xl md:text-4xl text-oastl-cream font-semibold leading-tight">
        Recruiting K-12 student co-plaintiffs.
      </h2>
      <p class="mt-5 text-[17px] text-oastl-cream/90 leading-relaxed font-serif">
        The next phase of the litigation names Oregon students as co-plaintiffs. Parents and guardians enroll on behalf of their children as Class A members ($1/year). Class A is the practical bridge between a family who cares and a student named in the case caption.
      </p>
      <a
        href="/join/#class-a"
        class="mt-7 inline-flex items-center gap-2 bg-oastl-gold text-oastl-forest px-5 py-3 rounded-sm font-medium hover:bg-oastl-cream transition-colors"
      >
        Become a student co-plaintiff →
      </a>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section 4 — Six duties of a trustee -->
  <section class="bg-oastl-bone">
    <div class="mx-auto max-w-5xl px-5 py-16">
      <div class="font-mono text-[11px] tracking-[0.22em] uppercase text-oastl-forest mb-2">
        Section 4 · The framework
      </div>
      <h2 class="font-serif text-3xl md:text-4xl text-oastl-ink font-semibold leading-tight">
        The six duties of a trustee.
      </h2>
      <p class="mt-4 text-oastl-ink/80 max-w-3xl leading-relaxed">
        Trust law is older than Oregon and older than the United States. It speaks in six duties. Together they tell you what the State of Oregon owes its schoolchildren — and where the failures lie.
      </p>
      <div class="mt-8">
        <TrusteeDuties />
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section 5 — Cross-bridge to Library Court Room -->
  <section class="bg-oastl-cream/40 border-t border-oastl-forest/15">
    <div class="mx-auto max-w-4xl px-5 py-16">
      <div class="font-mono text-[11px] tracking-[0.22em] uppercase text-oastl-forest mb-2">
        Section 5 · The broader record
      </div>
      <h2 class="font-serif text-2xl md:text-3xl text-oastl-ink font-semibold leading-tight mb-6">
        For the historical legal record across all twenty trust-lands states, the Library keeps a Court Room.
      </h2>
      <CrossBridge
        building="The Library"
        href="https://schooltrusts.net/court/"
        prompt="Open the Library’s Court Room"
        note="Centuries of trust-lands jurisprudence, organized for scholars and litigators."
      />
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
